# Call for Participation

**Reliability in the Age of AI**  
Berlin · September 10–11, 2026  
Signals Berlin is a small, single-track conference for practitioners working on reliability in the age of AI. We are deliberately keeping the program tight and the room highly relevant. The goal is not to maximize stage time. The goal is to create a high-quality conversation among people who are actively shaping this field.  
The main CFP will fill only a small number of slots. If you have something important to say, we encourage you to submit. And if your work belongs in this conversation, we encourage you to join us in Berlin regardless. Signals is designed as much for the hallway as for the stage.  
Our starting point is reliability engineering. We want to understand how AI is changing the way software is built, shipped, operated, observed, and kept reliable. At the same time, more and more production systems now depend directly on models, agents, retrieval pipelines, and other AI-heavy workloads. Signals is where these perspectives meet.  
We are looking for practitioner talks, field reports, emerging patterns, conceptual models, and honest lessons from the front lines. We welcome work in progress, unresolved questions, and early ideas that are grounded in real practice.

### Topics

We are especially interested in submissions on topics such as:  
**AI and software delivery**  
\* AI in coding, review, testing, and CI/CD  
\* deployment bottlenecks and maintenance risks from AI-produced code  
\* how AI is changing software engineering work, ownership, and delivery  
\* guardrails, review patterns, and control points for AI-assisted development  
**AI in software operations**  
\* AI in telemetry, monitoring, and alerting  
\* AI support in triage, escalation, runbooks, and repetitive operational workflows  
\* AI in incident response, investigation, and root-cause workflows  
\* copilots for on-call, debugging, and operational decision support  
\* postmortems, playbooks, knowledge capture, and incident management  
**Reliability of AI systems**  
\* operating LLM-powered products and model-driven systems in production  
\* observability for LLMs, agents, and retrieval-based applications  
\* debugging agentic workflows, evaluation loops, and failure cascades  
\* feedback loops, system behavior under uncertainty, and human oversight  
\* data quality, dark data, and operational blind spots in AI-heavy environments  
**Platform and organizational change**  
\* platform engineering for AI workflows and agentic systems  
\* interfaces between SRE, platform, data, and MLOps teams  
\* how reliability teams are evolving in the age of AI  
\* new operating models, feedback loops, and control surfaces for AI-enabled systems

### What makes a strong submission

We are looking for talks with:  
\* real operational experience  
\* clear lessons, tensions, or tradeoffs  
\* honest reflection on what worked, failed, or remains unresolved  
We care much more about substance than polish. A sharp practitioner talk beats a polished but thin presentation every time.

### What we are not looking for

Please do not submit:  
\* generic product AI talks or sales pitches  
\* broad "AI changes everything" narratives without operational depth  
\* abstract model research with no clear production consequences  
Vendor submissions are welcome, but the standard is the same: bring an honest technical perspective, real patterns from the field, and something useful for practitioners.

### Format and selection

Signals is deliberately small and highly curated. The main CFP will fill roughly 7 talk slots in the core program, with 30-minute sessions.  
Submissions will be reviewed by the Program Committee and selected for both individual quality and overall fit. Good submissions may still not be selected if they overlap with other talks or do not fit the final shape of the program.  
There will also be a separate lightning talk opportunity for ticket holders closer to the event.

### Timeline

**Main CFP opens:** March 19, 2026  
**Main CFP closes:** April 30, 2026  
**Program announced:** May 14, 2026  
If you are seeing important changes in reliability, software delivery, or operations because of AI, we would love to hear from you.  


